# --- luminaries --- #

toi:luminaries      a                   too:treeNode;
                    too:hasName         "luminaries";
                    too:hasTitle        "the luminaries";
                    too:hasNodeIcon     "spotlight";
                    too:hasNodeChild     _:norman;
                    too:hasNodeChild     _:dawkins;
                    too:hasNodeChild     _:pinker;
                    too:hasNodeChild     _:tufte;
	                  too:hasNodeParent   "influences";
                    too:hasNodeSummary
"""
these are some of the people who have not only informed my thinking on one particular 
subject or another, but have inspired me to question 'current thinking' in general.
many of the ideas espoused by these thinkers have been accepted and absorbed into 
our understanding of how the world works.  it can be easy to forget that their work
was once novel or controversial.
""".

_:norman				    a                   too:treeNode;
                    too:hasName         "norman";
                    too:hasNodeIcon     "norman";
                    too:hasTitle        "[http://www.jnd.org/ donald norman]";
                    too:hasNodeParent   "luminaries";
                    too:hasNodeSummary

"""
early on i read
[[wikipedia:The_Design_of_Everyday_Things|the design of everyday things]]
in which norman described aspects of good design, and where i learned the word
[[wikipedia:Affordance|affordance]].
he also talked about why many products might be systematically poorly designed.
in a more recent
[[youtube:RlQEoJaLQRA|ted design talk]]
he underscores the utility of beauty, and importance of factoring emotion into design.
""".

_:dawkins				    a                   too:treeNode;
                    too:hasName         "dawkins";
                    too:hasNodeIcon     "dawkins";
                    too:hasTitle        "[http://richarddawkins.net/ richard dawkins]";
                    too:hasNodeParent   "luminaries";
                    too:hasNodeSummary

"""
[[wikipedia:The_Selfish_Gene|the selfish gene]]
was a seminal book on evolution, from which we get the word
[[wikipedia:Meme|meme]].
it left me with an end-to-end understanding of the rise of life on earth.
dawkins is also an outspoken
[[wikipedia:Atheist|atheist]],
and proponent of
[[wikipedia:Rationalism|rationalism]].
he speaks clearly against magical thinking in all forms.
""".

_:pinker				    a                   too:treeNode;
                    too:hasName         "pinker";
                    too:hasNodeIcon     "pinker";
                    too:hasTitle         "[http://stevenpinker.com/biocv steven pinker]";
                    too:hasNodeParent   "luminaries";
                    too:hasNodeSummary

"""
i started with
[[wikipedia:The_Language_Instinct|the language instinct]],
which posits that humans are born with an innate capacity to develop grammatical language.
pinker often discusses interactions between language and behavior;
for example he gave an
[http://comment.rsablogs.org.uk/videos/ rsa animate]
talk on
[[youtube:3-son3EJTrU|indirect speech]].
i'm currently reading
[[wikipedia:The_Better_Angels_of_Our_Nature|the better angels of our nature]]
which, despite its gruesome descriptions of violence present and past, 
leaves me optimistic about the future.
""".

_:tufte				    	a                   too:treeNode;
                    too:hasName         "tufte";
                    too:hasNodeIcon     "tufte";
                    too:hasTitle         "[http://www.edwardtufte.com/tufte/ edward tufte]";
                    too:hasNodeParent   "luminaries";
                    too:hasNodeSummary
                    
"""
tufte's
[http://www.edwardtufte.com/tufte/courses one day course]
had a huge impact on my understanding of visual design.  he provides
a systematic approach for evaluating and improving visual representations.
if you work with pixels, check out tufte.
""".
